ce:section.ce:para:
Antibiotics refer to a description of secondary metabolites produced by microorganisms or higher organisms in the course of life, which have anti-pathogen ability. Tetracyclines (TCs) (Fig. 1
                     ) have been extensively used in veterinary, preventing and curing animal husbandry microbial diseases due to its considerable bioavailability and low price, including tetracycline (TC), oxytetracycline (OTC) and chlortetracycline (CTC), etc. However, the abuse of TCs brings about tremendous impair to human due to absorb residues passively through the food chain continuously, leading to liver damage, kidney injury, gastrointestinal reactions, even interfering the growth of teeth and bones [23]. Hence, the maximum residual amount of TCs is strictly limited by laws and regulations in China, the United States and the European Union. Nowadays, plenty of methods were used for detecting TCs, as shown in Table 1
                     , including colorimetry [24], enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay [25], MOF-based fluorescent sensing [26], high-performance liquid chromatography [27], etc. Nevertheless, although these methods are mature and accurate, their further application is limited due to the complexity of instruments and sample pretreatment, time-consuming, high cost and complex operation. Thus, establishing a rapid, economical, and practical method for the detection of TCs residues is imperative.

In view of the selectivity plays an integral part in the establishment of the detection performance of the carbon dot sensing system, the experiment was performing. We observed fluorescence spectra of representative ions under the condition of pH 7 and excitation wavelength of 365 nm, for the purpose of evaluating the selectivity of the sensing system, including Ba2+, NH4
                        +, Cd2+, Ca2+, Mg2+, Mn2+, Ni2+, Pb2+, Zn2+, Cl−, SO4
                        2− and NO3
                        −. In addition, some other common antibiotics were also investigated to evaluate selectivity, for instance, cephalosporins, quinolones, penicillins, aminoglycosides, chloramphenicols, macrolides and tetracyclines, etc. Surprisingly, there had a distinguished quenching feedback effect on CDs in the present of TCs (TC, CTC, OTC) among all the tested substances, while other substances have no more additional effects. Moreover, to further prove its good selectivity, sensitivity experiments were also conducted. An excessive 5 mM of other competing substances were mixing to compare with 50 µM TC, the results are represented in figure below (Fig. 6
                        ). Only slight influences happened to the fluorescence intensity even under excessive concentrations of other substances. Hence, we can draw a conclusion that the sensor was emerged fantastic selectivity and specificity to TCs compared with other substances. In this study for quantifying the sensitivity of the technique, TC was opted as the prototypical molecule to gauge TCs. The CDs were diluted with deionized water and got a last concentration of 0.1 mg/ml. Quickly mixed 1.8 ml of CDs and TC standard stock solutions of different concentrations in a test tube to obtain a CDs-TC system. Mixing analyte and CDs solution measuring their fluorescence intensity for linear investigation under normal conditions at a fluorescence excitation wavelength of 365 nm. The concentration of TC varies between 0.1 and 50 µM. The fluorescence intensity value of the CDs corresponding decreases when the TC concentration increases, indicating that CDs are extraordinary sensitive to TC (Fig. 7
                        ). In the range of 0.1–50 µM the concentration of TC shows a linear with quenching degree (F0-F)/F0 with the regression equation y = -0.0103x + 0.9481 and a correlation coefficient (R2) of 0.9941. The LOD (3σ/k) was calculated and the detection limit is 0.04 µM according to IUPAC regulations [33], where σ is the standard deviation of the fluorescence signal, and k is the slope of the line. Besides, as shown in Table 1, analytical characteristics such as sensitivity and linear range are comparable or even better than previous technique. Undoubtedly, TCs can be detected sensitively and specifically by applying CDs as a fluorescent sensor.
